commit bb3307b8ed
Author: Stephen Hicks <sdh@google.com>
Date:   10 years ago

    This is a combination of 8 commits:
    
    1.
    Leverage IArrayLike to improve type information
    Summary of changes:
      * goog.array methods use IArrayLike
      * goog.array.ArrayLike replaced with IArrayLike in closure
      * goog.dom methods updated to return appropriate IArrayLike collections
    
    RELNOTES: n/a
    
    2.
    Avoid using implicit conversions when calling Math functions.
    
    RELNOTES: n/a
    
    3.
    Only use the double click handler in goog.ui.Control if using IE 8 or
    earlier.
    
    This is due to the fact that in IE9+, the double click event sequence
    was changed to the standard, and so using the regular mousedown/mouseup
    events as well as the double click event handler causes
    performActionInternal to be fired three times when double clicking on a
    control.
    
    RELNOTES: Fix bug in goog.ui.Control for IE9+ where a double click caused performActionInternal to be fired three times.
    
    4.
    RELNOTES: Deprecate goog.i18n.BidiFormatter#spanWrap and spanWrapWithKnownDir.
    
    I plan to delete it soon.
    
    5.
    Delete deprecated goog.ui.DrilldownRow.unsafeCreate.
    
    RELNOTES[INC]: Breaking change for third parties: This will break your build if your code uses this method. Use goog.ui.DrilldownRow constructor instead.
    
    6.
    Delete deprecated goog.ui.tree.BaseNode#setHtml and setAfterLabelHtml.
    
    RELNOTES[INC]: Breaking change for third parties: This will break your build if your code uses these methods. Use setSafeHtml, setText and setAfterLabelSafeHtml instead.
    
    7.
    Fix Closure palette bug.
    
    Here is how to repro on HEAD demo:
      1) Using the top palette (1-8), select (click) on any number.
      2) Mouse over some other number (but don't click it), then move mouse
         outside of palette without mousing over any other number.
      3) Move mouse into empty cell (where 9 would go), or even alternately
         outside of the grid (but still inside of "Demo of the goog.ui.Palette"
         container), still taking care not to mouse over any other numbers.
      4) Click, and observe that the number moused over in step 2 is now both
         highlighted and selected, even though you never actually selected it
         through mouse or keyboard.
    
    Alternate keyboard demo of same bug:
      1) Move around the palette with keys. Noticed that moving only changes
         highlight state, not selection state. You must hit enter to select.
      2) When you have a square highlighted but not selected, take the mouse
         and focus somewhere else on the page.
      3) Refocus inside the top demo container using mouse.
      4) Notice the last highlighted square is re-highlighted (good) and also
         selected (bad). This is bad because the user never typed enter on this
         square or clicked on it. Simply refocusing the container should not
         make a selection.
    
    This behavior was introduced in CL 61183760. I have tried to fix the
    current bug while still leaving the bugfix from that CL intact. As such,
    the new behavior in step (4) above is that the last highlighted cell
    will get re-highlighted, but not selected. I believe this was the intent
    of that CL, and the selection state change is a side effect, but
    hopefully some of the people involved with that change can comment.
    
    RELNOTES: The behavior described in the bug report will go away.
    
    8.
    Disallow string in goog.History constructor.
    
    RELNOTES[INC]: Breaking change for third parties. This change will break your build if your code passes string as opt_blankPageUrl to goog.History constructor. Pass goog.html.TrustedResourceUrl instead.

